1
00:00:24,691 --> 00:00:26,459
DEFENDANT'S WAITING ROOM

2
00:00:27,027 --> 00:00:28,528
You understood what I just said, right?

3
00:00:28,795 --> 00:00:31,297
It means
we're changing our defense strategy.

4
00:00:31,364 --> 00:00:32,766
We're saying that Min Jun-guk is alive.

5
00:00:33,566 --> 00:00:35,702
It's because among the suspects...

6
00:00:38,605 --> 00:00:42,942
so don't feel fearful
in front of the jury, okay?

7
00:00:45,979 --> 00:00:46,946
What?

8
00:00:47,447 --> 00:00:49,582
How can you believe me
more than I do myself?

9
00:00:51,317 --> 00:00:53,520
How can you be sure that I didn't do it?

10
00:00:54,421 --> 00:00:57,457
I told you. You made a promise to me.

11
00:00:57,991 --> 00:01:00,060
That you would never hurt Min Jun-guk.

12
00:01:00,527 --> 00:01:04,464
Is that why you believe me?
Just because of a promise?

13
00:01:09,669 --> 00:01:11,137
Do you know what kind of person you are?

14
00:01:11,538 --> 00:01:15,708
You looked for me for ten years
to keep a promise I don't remember.

15
00:01:17,710 --> 00:01:18,778
Does that make sense?

16
00:01:19,279 --> 00:01:22,415
Ten years just to keep a simple promise.

17
00:01:28,655 --> 00:01:34,194
I admit that we doubted other suspects
without any grounds.

18
00:01:35,995 --> 00:01:39,132
But she said that all of the evidence
points towards only one person,

19
00:01:39,499 --> 00:01:43,036
the defendant Park Su-ha.

20
00:01:43,436 --> 00:01:45,905
But there is one more person.

21
00:01:49,542 --> 00:01:52,078
He was at the scene
on the day of the crime.

22
00:01:52,145 --> 00:01:54,047
And all of the circumstances match.

23
00:01:54,514 --> 00:01:58,384
There were phone records
and he was in possession of the knife.

24
00:01:58,451 --> 00:02:02,088
And he has the strength
to cut off a wrist.

25
00:02:02,422 --> 00:02:03,590
Who is that?

26
00:02:05,258 --> 00:02:08,328
It's the victim, Min Jun-guk.

27
00:02:09,395 --> 00:02:11,297
What are you saying?

28
00:02:11,364 --> 00:02:15,001
Min Jun-guk is the victim
who died in this crime.

29
00:02:16,269 --> 00:02:18,872
How can he be a suspect?

30
00:02:18,938 --> 00:02:20,607
Your Honor.

31
00:02:21,808 --> 00:02:23,743
And members of the jury.

32
00:02:23,810 --> 00:02:29,516
The defense is arguing that the victim
Min Jun-guk is still alive.

33
00:02:45,899 --> 00:02:49,669
Prosecution, Defense Counsel,
approach the bench.

34
00:02:55,642 --> 00:02:57,410
What's wrong with you?

35
00:02:57,710 --> 00:03:00,947
You should have mentioned this
during the preparation period.

36
00:03:01,214 --> 00:03:05,018
We would if we could have.
But we only just thought of it.

37
00:03:05,084 --> 00:03:07,220
This is very reckless.

38
00:03:07,320 --> 00:03:09,322
-Do you realize that?
-Yes, we do.

39
00:03:10,023 --> 00:03:13,826
But we think it's worth trying,
for the defendant's sake.

40
00:03:13,893 --> 00:03:15,295
This is a jury trial.

41
00:03:15,461 --> 00:03:19,098
We cannot accept any additional witnesses
or evidence.

42
00:03:20,200 --> 00:03:22,502
We'll prove it with the evidence we have.

43
00:03:24,537 --> 00:03:25,738
Understood.

44
00:03:26,105 --> 00:03:30,710
But you must know
that this is a very exceptional case.

45
00:03:31,811 --> 00:03:33,446
-Thank you.
-Thank you.

46
00:03:35,181 --> 00:03:40,253
Then let's begin with
Hwang Dal-jung's examination.

47
00:03:45,692 --> 00:03:47,560
Are you currently serving a sentence

48
00:03:47,627 --> 00:03:50,196
for the murder of your wife 26 years ago?

49
00:03:50,763 --> 00:03:51,731
Yes.

50
00:03:51,798 --> 00:03:55,602
It was called the "left-hand murder case"

51
00:03:55,668 --> 00:03:58,538
because only the left hand was found?

52
00:03:58,605 --> 00:03:59,739
Yes.

53
00:04:00,373 --> 00:04:05,078
Did you ever tell Min Jun-guk,
your old cellmate?

54
00:04:05,144 --> 00:04:06,246
DEFENDANT

55
00:04:06,913 --> 00:04:07,914
Yes, I did.

56
00:04:08,948 --> 00:04:10,383
PROSECUTOR

57
00:04:10,783 --> 00:04:13,953
Did you hear
that Min Jun-guk was murdered?

58
00:04:14,020 --> 00:04:15,021
Yes.

59
00:04:15,388 --> 00:04:17,757
Did you know that the evidence

60
00:04:17,824 --> 00:04:22,562
of the victim's murder was his left hand
found at the scene?

61
00:04:22,629 --> 00:04:23,663
No.

62
00:04:23,963 --> 00:04:27,800
Don't you think it's too much
of a coincidence?

63
00:04:28,601 --> 00:04:30,303
Yes, I think so.

64
00:04:31,104 --> 00:04:32,572
JURY

65
00:04:33,840 --> 00:04:36,743
Then let's consider
the following scenario.

66
00:04:37,277 --> 00:04:42,715
Min Jun-guk was wanted
for attempted murder and retaliation.

67
00:04:42,782 --> 00:04:46,486
He'd heard about the left-hand murder case
from this witness.

68
00:04:46,552 --> 00:04:48,788
And he got an idea.

69
00:04:49,489 --> 00:04:52,058
He would no longer be wanted
by the police.

70
00:04:52,358 --> 00:04:57,130
And he would be able to get revenge on
Park Su-ha, too.

71
00:04:57,230 --> 00:04:59,999
He would cut off his own left hand.

72
00:05:00,066 --> 00:05:03,102
And make it look
as though Park Su-ha had murdered him.

73
00:05:04,003 --> 00:05:09,042
Objection! Counsel is distorting the truth
through speculation.

74
00:05:09,108 --> 00:05:11,344
Isn't the prosecution's charge also
based on speculation?

75
00:05:11,411 --> 00:05:13,346
Only the left hand was found.

76
00:05:13,413 --> 00:05:16,015
The rest of the body has never been found.

77
00:05:16,082 --> 00:05:19,018
Without having the body
from the beginning,

78
00:05:19,085 --> 00:05:24,123
considering this a murder case is
just speculation. No, it's a guess.

79
00:05:35,868 --> 00:05:37,503
On May 30, 2012,

80
00:05:37,570 --> 00:05:41,007
did Park Su-ha come
to the police station to threaten you?

81
00:05:44,444 --> 00:05:45,478
Yes.

82
00:05:46,879 --> 00:05:48,414
What was the threat?

83
00:05:52,819 --> 00:05:57,223
"If you don't do anything,
I might go and kill Min Jun-guk."

84
00:05:57,890 --> 00:05:59,392
That's what he said.

85
00:06:00,727 --> 00:06:02,528
If Min Jun-guk were killed,

86
00:06:02,729 --> 00:06:07,967
who would be the first suspect
to come to mind?

87
00:06:13,206 --> 00:06:14,107
Park Su-ha.

88
00:06:24,717 --> 00:06:25,918
Nothing further.

89
00:06:31,958 --> 00:06:32,792
POLICE'S TESTIMONY

90
00:06:32,859 --> 00:06:36,929
Did you lose your gun on May 31, 2012?

91
00:06:36,996 --> 00:06:38,131
What?

92
00:06:42,001 --> 00:06:43,903
If you don't tell the truth,
I'll kill you.

93
00:06:43,970 --> 00:06:45,605
I'm watching you.

94
00:06:47,874 --> 00:06:49,809
Yes, I did.

95
00:06:50,109 --> 00:06:53,713
Did you name Park Su-ha as the thief?

96
00:06:55,314 --> 00:06:58,951
-Yes.
-Did he really take it?

97
00:06:59,018 --> 00:07:01,821
No. I was mistaken.

98
00:07:02,255 --> 00:07:07,860
Did you suspect Park Su-ha
as the murderer because of that?

99
00:07:10,763 --> 00:07:14,367
-I'm not sure...
-Nothing further.

100
00:07:17,470 --> 00:07:18,871
NOT CREDIBLE

101
00:07:24,977 --> 00:07:25,845
POLICE TESTIMONY

102
00:07:25,912 --> 00:07:29,449
This knife, which was allegedly used
during the murder,

103
00:07:29,515 --> 00:07:32,218
was the same knife
that the defendant carried around

104
00:07:32,285 --> 00:07:34,787
and had his fingerprints all over it.

105
00:07:35,388 --> 00:07:38,791
Min Jun-guk's fingerprints were also
on that knife.

106
00:07:38,858 --> 00:07:44,430
And this knife was taken
by Min Jun-guk when he fled

107
00:07:44,497 --> 00:07:46,999
after harming Jang Hye-seong
and Park Su-ha a week before the incident.

108
00:07:47,066 --> 00:07:51,737
Thus, the last person to have the knife
in his hand was Min Jun-guk.

109
00:07:52,405 --> 00:07:54,407
FINGERPRINTS ON KNIFE CANNOT BE CONSIDERED
AS EVIDENCE

110
00:07:54,674 --> 00:07:58,978
According to Min Jun-guk's phone records,
the last person...

111
00:08:01,948 --> 00:08:03,850
he talked to was Park Su-ha.

112
00:08:05,885 --> 00:08:06,786
PHONE CALL RECORD

113
00:08:06,853 --> 00:08:09,188
The victim was the one who called,

114
00:08:09,255 --> 00:08:11,057
and the defendant answered his phone.

115
00:08:11,190 --> 00:08:13,125
If he had the intent to murder
at their meeting,

116
00:08:13,192 --> 00:08:15,595
the defendant should've been the one
to make the call.

117
00:08:17,964 --> 00:08:19,932
DEFENDANT DIDN'T INITIATE THE CALL

118
00:08:20,132 --> 00:08:23,503
Quite a lot of blood was found
at the scene.

119
00:08:23,569 --> 00:08:25,605
The left hand was found as well.

120
00:08:25,671 --> 00:08:28,508
The defense can only make their argument

121
00:08:28,574 --> 00:08:32,812
when they bring evidence
that Min Jun-guk is alive.

122
00:08:35,014 --> 00:08:35,882
EVIDENCE

123
00:08:36,082 --> 00:08:37,683
Likewise,
the prosecution should have indicted

124
00:08:37,750 --> 00:08:41,687
with sufficient evidence
of the victim's actual death.

125
00:08:41,754 --> 00:08:44,090
The amount of blood found was not fatal.

126
00:08:44,156 --> 00:08:48,728
And, the left hand alone does not prove
that he is dead.

127
00:08:49,095 --> 00:08:50,229
DEAD BODY...?

128
00:08:50,663 --> 00:08:52,098
They're doing well.

129
00:08:53,165 --> 00:08:55,968
They've eliminated most of the evidence.

130
00:08:57,069 --> 00:08:58,170
THE END

131
00:09:12,885 --> 00:09:15,521
Wow! This is so good.

132
00:09:15,588 --> 00:09:17,857
How much for a box?

133
00:09:17,924 --> 00:09:19,025
Fifty thousand won.

134
00:09:19,091 --> 00:09:22,028
They're 10,000 won a piece in Seoul.

135
00:09:22,695 --> 00:09:24,664
Can you wrap it up
so I can take it with me?

136
00:09:24,730 --> 00:09:27,800
-Sure. One box?
-No, two.

137
00:09:30,469 --> 00:09:35,274
What was Park Su-ha like?
I heard she's really pretty.

138
00:09:35,341 --> 00:09:36,509
Is she curvy?

139
00:09:36,909 --> 00:09:39,912
Yes, she was tall and very curvy.

140
00:09:41,047 --> 00:09:42,214
Really?

141
00:09:43,215 --> 00:09:44,684
But Park Su-ha is a guy.

142
00:09:47,553 --> 00:09:50,523
See? You've never seen Park Su-ha.

143
00:09:50,590 --> 00:09:52,224
How did you know to report him?

144
00:09:53,726 --> 00:09:57,196
Get out.
You're here to get my reward, right?

145
00:09:57,263 --> 00:10:00,032
I'm not selling my peaches to you, so go!

146
00:10:00,633 --> 00:10:02,501
-Go!
-Ouch.

147
00:10:02,568 --> 00:10:06,439
I didn't come for the reward!
I swear. It's true.

148
00:10:06,505 --> 00:10:09,308
Just tell me how you knew to report him.

149
00:10:17,216 --> 00:10:20,319
Let me in!

150
00:10:20,386 --> 00:10:21,887
Open the door!

151
00:10:23,456 --> 00:10:26,392
Each side has presented their evidence.
Now, it's time for closing arguments.

152
00:10:26,459 --> 00:10:28,828
Prosecution, please go first.

153
00:10:34,400 --> 00:10:38,037
Last year, I was
in charge of a murder case.

154
00:10:38,504 --> 00:10:40,840
It was a case where the murderer killed

155
00:10:41,374 --> 00:10:43,509
the mother of the person
against whom he had a grudge.

156
00:10:44,477 --> 00:10:47,580
There was plenty of evidence
to prove the defendant did it.

157
00:10:48,381 --> 00:10:49,915
He had a grudge.

158
00:10:50,282 --> 00:10:53,185
He was seen on surveillance video
on his way to break the camera.

159
00:10:53,252 --> 00:10:56,956
There was a fracture on the victim's head
caused by a blow to the head.

160
00:10:57,957 --> 00:11:00,393
It was clearly murder.

161
00:11:04,597 --> 00:11:07,199
Of course, that was according
to my criteria.

162
00:11:10,136 --> 00:11:13,773
But the defense argued
that it was an accident.

163
00:11:14,373 --> 00:11:18,144
The victim hit her head
when she fainted from arrhythmia.

164
00:11:18,210 --> 00:11:20,513
And the broken security camera was just
a coincidence.

165
00:11:20,713 --> 00:11:23,649
The defense also argued it wasn't arson,
but a simple fire,

166
00:11:25,518 --> 00:11:31,290
saying it was a tragedy caused
by a lot of coincidences.

167
00:11:32,558 --> 00:11:34,126
They argued there was reasonable doubt.

168
00:11:34,193 --> 00:11:36,262
REASONABLE DOUBT:
DOUBT IN A DEFENDANT'S GUILT

169
00:11:36,328 --> 00:11:39,465
In the end,
the defendant was found not guilty.

170
00:11:39,532 --> 00:11:45,004
And he terrorized the people he resented
right after his release.

171
00:11:51,777 --> 00:11:54,113
There were many pieces of evidence.

172
00:11:54,280 --> 00:11:58,617
But he was found not guilty
with only 80 of 100 pieces.

173
00:11:59,585 --> 00:12:03,389
Because the remaining 20 pieces
could be made to form a different picture,

174
00:12:03,456 --> 00:12:07,493
with that reasonable doubt,
the defendant pleaded not guilty.

175
00:12:11,363 --> 00:12:14,600
Just because you assembled 80 pieces
of that 100 piece elephant puzzle,

176
00:12:14,667 --> 00:12:18,704
that doesn't mean the elephant
looks like a lion or a cat.

177
00:12:19,271 --> 00:12:23,442
Even a child can see it's an elephant
before it's finished.

178
00:12:23,943 --> 00:12:29,849
You must know what the picture is
from the puzzle I have shown you today.

179
00:12:30,349 --> 00:12:32,151
The knife covered
with the defendant's fingerprints.

180
00:12:32,218 --> 00:12:34,253
A grudge. Phone records.

181
00:12:34,320 --> 00:12:37,056
The defendant's confession
and the left hand.

182
00:12:38,257 --> 00:12:42,294
To ensure all this evidence doesn't go
to waste as it did in last year's trial,

183
00:12:42,695 --> 00:12:46,432
and that a murderer
doesn't get away with his crime,

184
00:12:46,499 --> 00:12:50,536
members of the jury,
I ask that you make a wise decision.

185
00:13:02,381 --> 00:13:03,449
Next.

186
00:13:04,450 --> 00:13:06,585
Counsel, your closing statement.

187
00:13:17,797 --> 00:13:18,731
I'll do it.

188
00:13:19,999 --> 00:13:21,500
Let me do it.

189
00:13:37,983 --> 00:13:43,422
I would like to thank the jury
for sitting through this long trial.

190
00:13:44,623 --> 00:13:47,459
I would like to tell you something
before I close.

191
00:13:47,960 --> 00:13:50,429
The prosecutor mentioned a case to you.

192
00:13:53,098 --> 00:13:56,802
The victim of that case was my mother.

193
00:14:08,280 --> 00:14:14,119
Then, I cried out that reasonable doubt
and the presumption of innocence

194
00:14:15,287 --> 00:14:18,224
were all rubbish.

195
00:14:21,360 --> 00:14:25,998
I wanted to wring the necks of those
who had created such principles.

196
00:14:30,035 --> 00:14:35,007
But today, I finally realized
why we need such principles.

197
00:14:39,511 --> 00:14:43,883
Can you believe it?
I hated those principles so much.

198
00:14:43,949 --> 00:14:46,185
But I'm using them to defend a person,

199
00:14:46,418 --> 00:14:47,887
and desperately at that.

200
00:14:54,226 --> 00:14:59,331
The defendant has no memory
of what he did one year ago.

201
00:14:59,798 --> 00:15:03,702
And Min Jun-guk's left hand was found.

202
00:15:04,770 --> 00:15:06,338
There are two possibilities.

203
00:15:06,805 --> 00:15:10,075
One is that the defendant
really did kill the victim.

204
00:15:10,142 --> 00:15:14,480
Or that Min Jun-guk set this up
and disappeared.

205
00:15:17,750 --> 00:15:24,623
If, after this trial, you think
in your heart that both are possibilities,

206
00:15:24,690 --> 00:15:26,191
then the verdict should be not guilty.

207
00:15:26,792 --> 00:15:31,263
When in doubt,
you must rule in favor of the defendant.

208
00:15:31,330 --> 00:15:33,465
That's the principle of a criminal trial.

209
00:15:35,968 --> 00:15:40,606
The prosecutor said this case is
like a puzzle with missing pieces.

210
00:15:41,440 --> 00:15:46,545
Of course, an elephant won't look
like a lion because of that.

211
00:15:46,612 --> 00:15:49,748
But because there are missing pieces,
we can't tell

212
00:15:50,349 --> 00:15:56,255
if the elephant is killing someone
or kicking a ball.

213
00:16:00,059 --> 00:16:05,597
What if you saw an unfinished puzzle
of an elephant...

214
00:16:05,664 --> 00:16:10,703
and judged that the elephant
should be punished for killing a person?

215
00:16:12,171 --> 00:16:14,340
And what if after you kill the elephant
you finish the puzzle,

216
00:16:14,406 --> 00:16:19,311
and you find out that it was a ball,
not a person in front of the elephant?

217
00:16:22,214 --> 00:16:24,950
We cannot revive a dead elephant.

218
00:16:27,653 --> 00:16:29,355
It's the same with the defendant.

219
00:16:29,421 --> 00:16:34,660
If he were to get a long sentence
and spend his best years in jail,

220
00:16:36,128 --> 00:16:38,597
we cannot return the time he lost.

221
00:16:45,838 --> 00:16:48,540
That's why we need those damn principles.

222
00:17:00,386 --> 00:17:05,624
They may be damn principles
that let my mother's murderer free.

223
00:17:15,567 --> 00:17:20,072
But those principles are the same
upright principles

224
00:17:20,139 --> 00:17:22,141
that can save the defendant before you.

225
00:17:39,358 --> 00:17:40,659
The jury has gone into deliberation.

226
00:17:40,726 --> 00:17:42,394
JURY DELIBERATION:
TIME TAKEN TO REACH A VERDICT

227
00:17:42,461 --> 00:17:43,695
Where are you, Yu-chang?

228
00:17:43,762 --> 00:17:46,331
I'm on my way back to Seoul.

229
00:17:46,398 --> 00:17:48,300
Did you get anything out of Mun Sung-nam?

230
00:17:49,268 --> 00:17:52,471
No. I waited. But she didn't come out.

231
00:17:52,771 --> 00:17:54,940
Okay. See you tomorrow.

232
00:18:03,315 --> 00:18:04,383
Jang Hye-seong.

233
00:18:05,417 --> 00:18:07,019
What?

234
00:18:07,219 --> 00:18:08,520
Let me ask you something.

235
00:18:09,021 --> 00:18:11,390
Don't you feel sorry to your mother?

236
00:18:12,458 --> 00:18:14,059
No. Why?

237
00:18:14,626 --> 00:18:20,599
Your defense was what Mr. Cha used
in your mother's case last year.

238
00:18:21,700 --> 00:18:22,801
I know.

239
00:18:23,535 --> 00:18:26,338
Do you mean that Mr. Cha was right?

240
00:18:26,605 --> 00:18:29,041
He let your mother's murderer free
with that logic.

241
00:18:33,278 --> 00:18:34,313
Yes.

242
00:18:37,349 --> 00:18:38,484
I think Mr. Cha...

243
00:18:40,052 --> 00:18:41,920
did his job as a lawyer.

244
00:18:45,190 --> 00:18:48,060
I feel really sorry to your mother.

245
00:18:49,161 --> 00:18:52,164
How upset must she be
if she knew you did this.

246
00:18:52,231 --> 00:18:55,267
No. She would say I was right.

247
00:18:56,568 --> 00:18:57,903
That I am right.

248
00:18:59,104 --> 00:19:00,973
She'd say I'm doing the right thing.

249
00:19:02,674 --> 00:19:05,310
-I don't think so--
-She's my mother.

250
00:19:06,044 --> 00:19:07,412
I know her best.

251
00:19:09,348 --> 00:19:10,449
I'm sure.

252
00:19:12,918 --> 00:19:14,253
She would tell me that I did well.

253
00:19:58,730 --> 00:20:02,000
Mom. Am I right?

254
00:20:04,570 --> 00:20:07,940
I did the right thing? Didn't I?

255
00:21:22,247 --> 00:21:23,348
What time is it?

256
00:21:27,886 --> 00:21:29,054
It's 10:50.

257
00:21:31,523 --> 00:21:33,292
